    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    Aline Burch replies on behalf of Leonard Woolf to explain that The Hogarth Press have just reprinted The Common Reader first series as a uniform edition and the second series is now being bound. She relays that a Penguin reprint would have an adverse effect on the sales of the uniform edition and therefore cannot renew their contracts with Penguin
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>
                            West Drayton, Middx.
                        </placeName>
                        <date when="1948-07-08">
                            8th July, 1948.
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>
                            <orgName>Penguin Books</orgName>
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>
                            West Drayton, Middx.
                        </addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>
                        Dear Sir,
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    	<persName>Mr.Woolf</persName> has asked me to reply<lb/>
                    to your letter to him of <date when="1948-06-30">June 30</date>,<lb/>
                    and to explain the position with<lb/>
                    regard to <title>THE COMMON READER</title>, Series<lb/>
                    I and II.  We, ourselves, have just<lb/>
                    been able to reprint the First Series<lb/>
                    in our Uniform Edition at 7/6d. and<lb/>
                    the Second Series is at the binders,<lb/>
                    and <persName>Mr.Woolf</persName> feels that the issue of<lb/>
                    a 1/6d <orgName>Penguin</orgName> reprint, at the same<lb/>
                    time, cannot fail to have an adverse<lb/>
                    affect on the sales of the Uniform<lb/>
                    Edition.  In the circumstances, there-<lb/>
                    fore, he would very much prefer not<lb/>
                    to renew the <orgName>Penguin</orgName> contracts, at<lb/>
                    any rate for the present.<lb/>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        Yours faithfully,
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                    Secretary to <persName>Mr.Woolf</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
